  journal   = {Clinics},
  year      = {2018},
  month     = {November},
  annote    = { This review examines various tools and technologies used to improve communication skills in children with autism spectrum disorder. There are low-tech systems like PECS to high-tech devices such as tablets and virtual reality (VR). Each shows varying degrees of effectiveness. Techniques like TEACCH and PECS have had mixed results, responsive methods like RPMT have shown promise in improving communication and language skills. Tablets with apps like Proloquo2Go and speech-generating devices also have positive effects. Emerging VR technologies show potential for enhancing social communication but are still in early stages. Despite limitations in the studies, including small sample sizes, these findings emphasize the importance of personalized interventions to improve communication, social interaction, and development for children with ASD.}
